{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 PURGATORIO CANTO 30}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 1-7.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This first simile in a canto that is heavily similetic seems deliberately difficult.  \softline
Puzzled out, it compares the sevenfold spirit of the Church Triumphant, toward which all in the \softline
procession now turn for guidance as they do above in the Empyrean, to the Little Dipper, which \softline
locates the North Star for earthly navigators.  The first heaven is either that of the moon (starting \softline
upward from earth) or the Empyrean (starting from the other end of Dante's universe).  Since \softline
there are no groups of stars in either of these spheres, we realize immediately that we are here \softline
dealing with metaphoric language.  (Sam Glucksberg's book [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Understanding Figurative \softline
Language: From Metaphors to Idioms}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2001)] on figurative \softline
language begins [p. 3] with the story of a colleague of his who, a linguist, was on his way to a \softline
conference in Israel.  Interrogated by security personnel at the airport, he said he was going to a \softline
conference on metaphor.  His interrogator wanted to know what metaphor is.  When the linguist \softline
hesitated, as one might well do, he was dragged away for an hour's worth of detention and \softline
questioning before a local professor could vouch for his credentials and help set him on his way.)  \softline
The sevenfold Spirit of God [see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXIX.64-66]) seems clearly to be identified \softline
with the Holy Spirit, one aspect of the triune God in the Empyrean.  Porena (comm. to vv. 1-9) \softline
points out that the stars of the constellation Ursa (whether Major or Minor) were construed as \softline
seven ploughing oxen, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 septem triones}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , as is reflected in Dante's word 'settentr{\f3 \'56}on' (which may \softline
reflect Virgil's 'septem... trioni' at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Georgics}{\plain \fs24 \f1  III.381).  Sapegno (comm. to verse 1) noted that \softline
Dante had already (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Rime}{\plain \fs24 \f1  C.29) referred to 'le sette stelle gelide unquemai' (referring to Europe, \softline
located in the hemisphere that 'never [loses] the seven freezing stars'), translating Boethius's \softline
'septem gelidi triones' (seven frigid oxen -- }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Cons}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.6m.10), also cited (later) in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Monarchia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
II.viii.13.  This higher sevenfold spirit, unlike Ursa Minor, never rises or sets but is constantly \softline
glowing with charity; it is also never hidden by a clouded sky, even though it is not visible to us \softline
because we exist in a 'cloud' of our own sinfulness.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 8-9.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The twenty-four elders, representing the Old Testament, turn toward the chariot as \softline
to the awaited messiah who, in His first coming, crowned their time of militance with peace and \softline
who now will come in Judgment.  See Ephesians 2:14, 'Ipse enim est pax nostra' (For He is our \softline
peace), a text cited by Singleton (comm. to verse 9).  Since the procession in the garden \softline
represents the Church Triumphant, the mystical body of Christ }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 after}{\plain \fs24 \f1  its progress through history, \softline
it seems advisable to realize that we deal here with a scene that is meant to reflect the final advent \softline
of Christ for the Day of Judgment.  See Singleton (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Journey to Beatrice}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Cambridge: Harvard \softline
University Press, 1967 (1958)]), pp. 72-85, citing St. Bernard on the three advents of Christ \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Patrologia Latina}{\plain \fs24 \f1  183, col. 35ff.).  See also Thomas Merton ("Le Sacrement de l'Avent dans la \softline
spiritualit{\f2\u233\'e9} de saint Bernard," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dieu Vivant}{\plain \fs24 \f1  23 [1953], pp. 23-43), Mark Musa (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Advent at the \softline
Gates}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Bloomington, IN: Indiana University Press, 1974]), and the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VIII.103-108.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 10-12.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The elder who sings alone is clearly the Song of Songs, whether the book itself or \softline
its 'author,' Solomon, his words repeating the phrasing 'Veni..., veni..., veni' of the Canticle of \softline
Canticles 4:8 ('Come from Lebanon, my bride, come from Lebanon, come').  We would be \softline
forgiven if we believed we were about to witness a wedding ceremony of some kind, featuring \softline
Beatrice in the role of bride.  A strange 'wedding' it will turn out to be, characterized by tears 
more than by smiles.  In fact, no canto in the poem displays more words for weeping than this one \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXXIII has exactly as many): }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 lagrime}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (vv. 91, 145), }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 lagrimando}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (54),}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1  piangere}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (56, 57, \softline
107, 141).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Eugenio Chiarini ({\u8220\'93}}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  Canto XXX,{\u8221\'94} in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis Scaligera}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Florence: Le \softline
Monnier, 1967]), p. 1112, points out that these verses constitute the longest sentence (12 lines) in \softline
the poem.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 13-15.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The reference is to the trumpet blast that will summon the souls of the dead to \softline
judgment (I Corinthians 15:52).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The word 'hallelujah' seems so familiar that it may be surprising to discover that it occurs \softline
(and occurs four times) only in a single biblical text, the nineteenth chapter of John's Book of \softline
Revelation, where the saints (Apoc. 19:1, 19:3), the elders and the four gospel beasts (Apoc. \softline
19:4), and a great multitude (Apoc. 19:6, reasonably understood as the souls of the blessed, to \softline
whom, in fact, Dante refers here) all cry out this word in welcome of the coming reign of the true \softline
God and of his Judgment.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab There have been and remain disputes about the words }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 voce}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (voice) and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 alleluiare}{\plain \fs24 \f1  as well \softline
as the grammatical construction in verse 15.  We have followed Petrocchi (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 La Commedia secondo \softline
l'antica vulgata}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Florence: Le Lettere, 1994 (1966)], vol. I, Introduzione), pp. 218-20, in \softline
agreement with the decisions he has made, which seem all the stronger for being in complete \softline
accord with the gloss found in Benvenuto da Imola (comm. to vv. 13-18): the saved souls will \softline
sing songs of praise with the restored bodily instruments they possessed in their first lives.  The \softline
manuscript tradition produced two major variants here, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 alleviare}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (to lighten) rather than \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 alleluiare}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (to sing hallelujah), }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 carne}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (flesh) rather than }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 voce}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  Some also question (e.g., Chiavacci \softline
Leonardi [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio, con il commento di A. M. C. L.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (Milan: Mondadori, 1994)], p. 903) the \softline
notion that Dante is here using a rare (for him) ablative absolute, as most believe he in fact is.  In \softline
order to support that reading, such as Chiavacci Leonardi must interpret the verb }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 alleluiare}{\plain \fs24 \f1  to \softline
mean 'to make beautiful with a hallelujah,' which, given the context of Revelation 19, seems \softline
palliative, a rather latter-day pre-Raphaelite reading of the verse.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 16-18.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   As will arise all those who will be saved at the Last Judgment, a hundred angels \softline
('ministers and messengers of life eternal') rise up upon the chariot itself to welcome Beatrice, \softline
who, in a moment, will come to it.  Where do these angels come from?  We are not told whether \softline
they suddenly manifest themselves upon the chariot now just as Beatrice comes, or descended \softline
from the Empyrean with her, or with the chariot when it came to show itself to Dante in Eden.  \softline
See the notes to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXXI.77-78 and XXXII.89-90.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab These Beatricean angels have a pre-history.  In }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Vita nuova}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIII.7 Dante imagines \softline
Beatrice's death and sees a band of angels who return with her to heaven, mounting after a little \softline
white cloud, and singing 'Osanna in altissimis.'  Charles Singleton (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia, Elements of \softline
Structure}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Cambridge: Harvard University Press, 1965 (1954)]), p. 57, was perhaps the first to \softline
make the necessary connections between that scene and this one.  This procession began with \softline
voices singing 'Hosanna' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXIX.51); Beatrice returns with her host of angels and again she \softline
is obscured by a cloud.  The affinities between the two scenes and the Bible are even more \softline
suggestive than Singleton noticed.  In the prose of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Vita nuova}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIII Dante says that he seemed \softline
to hear the words 'Osanna in excelsis.'  The precise phrase occurs -- strange as it may seem, given \softline
its familiarity -- only once in the Latin New Testament, in Mark 11:10.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \ul0 \tab These verses draw Dante's imagining of Beatrice's departure from this life in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Vita nuova}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
into obvious relation to his presentation of her return to earth here in the garden of Eden.  In both \softline
cases the word 'Hosanna' associates her with Christ's triumphal entry into Jerusalem: in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Vita \softline
nuova}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , the New Jerusalem that is life eternal in the Empyrean; here, a triumphant descent to earth \softline
modeled on Christ's return in judgment.  It is thus that one can answer Peter Armour's question \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante's Griffin and the History of the World: A Study of the Earthly Paradise ["Purgatorio" \softline
XXIX-XXXIII]}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Oxford: Clarendon, 1989], pp. 56-58): if Beatrice represents Christ (and Armour \softline
believes that she does), then how can the griffin also do so?  The griffin stands for Christ as the \softline
equivalent of his Church, His mystical body, represented by the chariot.  The reader might imagine \softline
a film version of this scene, with all the 'characters' in the procession (but not Dante and Matelda -- or Statius and Virgil) as cartoon figures, and Beatrice played by a living actress.  The Church \softline
Triumphant, appearing on this unique occasion in the earthly paradise for the instruction of Dante, \softline
is otherwise always located in the Empyrean (whence it will descend for his instruction in \softline
actuality, not only symbolically, in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIII), awaiting a future and final series of events.  \softline
Beatrice comes as Christ will come in that future, in the Second Coming (his third advent -- see \softline
the note to vv. 8-9).  This temporal distinction helps us to understand that there is indeed a \softline
difference between the symbolic griffin and Beatrice as figure of Christ to come in judgment, that \softline
there is not a question of 'two Christs,' but of two differing kinds of representation of the same \softline
Christ.  In }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXXII.89-90 we learn that the griffin has returned to the Empyrean, \softline
leaving Beatrice and the chariot behind in the garden, now representing the Church Militant's \softline
career from its founding into the fourteenth century.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 16.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The rare word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 basterna}{\plain \fs24 \f1  has caused difficulty.  Benvenuto (comm. to vv. 13-18) says \softline
that it is a vehicle made of soft skins, used to transport noble women; he suggests that it fits the \softline
context here because it is drawn by two animals (this chariot, he notes, is pulled by a two-natured \softline
beast) and because Beatrice is the most noble of women.  According to Servius's gloss of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
VIII.666 (cited first by Lombardi [comm. to this verse] and then by Trucchi [comm. to vv. 13-21]), the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 basterna}{\plain \fs24 \f1  was a cart, festooned with veils, found in Gaul, where it was used to transport \softline
chaste matrons to sacred festivals.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 17.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The Latin phrase }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 ad vocem tanti senis}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (at the words of so great an elder) is Dante's \softline
own, opening a series of three rhyming Latin endings of lines, the next two from Mark and Virgil \softline
respectively.  The effect is to make three Latin 'authors,' Dante, Mark, and Virgil, each contribute \softline
part of a Latin verse for the advent of Beatrice.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 19.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Beatrice's hundred angels cite the first of the two master texts for this poem found in \softline
this tercet, the Bible and the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  The clause 'Bless{\f3 \'50}d are you who come' (with the adjective \softline
given a startling masculine ending, not the feminine that would seem a more fitting \softline
accompaniment to Beatrice) is derived from the account of Christ's entry into Jerusalem found in \softline
Mark 11:9-10: 'And they that went before, and they that followed, cried, saying, "Hosanna; \softline
Bless{\f3 \'50}d is he that comes (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Benedictus qui venit}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) in the name of the Lord.  Bless{\f3 \'50}d be the kingdom \softline
of our father David, that comes in the name of the Lord: Hosanna in the highest" (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Hosanna in \softline
excelsis}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ).'  While Matthew (31:9) and John (12:13) also report the 'Hosanna' and the blessedness \softline
of him who comes in fulfilment of the prophecy in Zechariah 9:9, only Mark has the words almost \softline
exactly as Dante has them in this passage and in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Vita nuova}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIII.7 (see the note to vv. 16-18 
and Hollander ["Dante's Use of the Fiftieth Psalm," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  91 (1973)], p. 146).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Dante could just as easily have said 'benedicta' as 'benedictus'; neither rhyme nor meter \softline
forced his hand.  We must therefore understand that the scandalous regendering of Beatrice \softline
caused by the correct citation of Mark's gospel is deliberate.  It seems clear that the poet wants his \softline
reader to realize that her meaning, her eventual identity, is totally involved in Christ.  And thus she \softline
comes as Christ, not as herself.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 20.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The angelic strewing has reminded commentators, at least since the time of Daniello \softline
(comm. to vv. 19-21), of the strewing of palm fronds in the path of Jesus on what became known \softline
as Palm Sunday.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 21.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The Latin is Virgilian (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VI.883): 'Give lilies with full hands.'  This is the climax of \softline
Anchises' tearful and prophetic speech about the future of Rome and the dreadful loss of \softline
Marcellus, the adoptive son of Augustus who was to rule Rome after the emperor's death, but \softline
who beat his 'father' to the grave.  In Virgil's text the lilies are flowers of mourning; in Dante's \softline
they seem rather to be associated with (according to Pietro di Dante [comm. to verse 20]) the \softline
Song of Songs (2:1), when the bride describes herself as the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 lilium convallium}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , 'lily of the valley,' \softline
a wildflower, not a cultivated plant.  Dante will later associate lilies with the Apostles (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
XXIII.74).  Traditionally, a flowering bough in the form of a lily was borne by the angel Gabriel in \softline
depictions of the Annunciation, denoting the chastity of Mary (see Fallani's comment to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
XXXII.112).  It seems clear that here the lilies are relocated symbolically, losing their tragic tone \softline
for a 'comic' and celebratory one; they have a positive and redemptive valence, not the funerary \softline
significance that they have in Virgil's line.  At the same time, for those of us who are thinking of \softline
Virgil as well as of Beatrice, they do underline our (and soon Dante's) sadness at this 'death' of \softline
Virgil in the poem.  In that respect the verse functions in both a 'Beatricean' and a 'Virgilian' \softline
mode.  For a remarkably 'Dantean' and Christian reading of Virgil's verse by St. Ambrose, see \softline
Lino Pertile (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 La puttana e il gigante: Dal Cantico dei Cantici al Paradiso Terrestre di Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
[Ravenna: Longo, 1998]), p. 64.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab This is the closest Dante comes to giving a piece of Virgil's Latin text an uninterrupted \softline
verbatim presence in his poem.  His Italian 'oh,' however, does interrupt the flow of the Virgilian \softline
line.  It seems more than possible that the exclamation is spoken, since it is uttered by her angels, \softline
to mark the moment of Beatrice's appearance on the chariot.  This may also be the moment at \softline
which Virgil disappears -- although that hypothesis is perhaps less sustainable.  That the Italian \softline
interjection 'oh!' is meant to reflect Isidore of Seville's description (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Etym}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.xiv) of interjections \softline
(literally, according to Isidore, words placed between other words) as being difficult to translate \softline
into any other language, see Hollander (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Il Virgilio dantesco: tragedia nella "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
[Florence: Olschki, 1983]), p. 143, n. 46.  The fact that Virgil's sad and beautiful Latin line is \softline
interrupted by an Italian interjection was probably dictated by more than the metrical requirements \softline
of Dante's hendecasyllabic line.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 22-33.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This third simile in the canto, when compared with the convoluted first one, is \softline
simplicity itself, as though Beatrice's presence itself called for a less self-conscious artistry on the \softline
part of the poet.  Nonetheless, once again Dante's beloved is associated, at least intrinsically, by \softline
the iconography of the rising sun, with Christ.  For a discussion of this and many other of the \softline
poet's similarly ineffable experiences in the earthly paradise see Giusppe Ledda (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 La guerra della 
lingua}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Ravenna: Longo, 2002]), pp. 223-42.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 31-33.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Beatrice, described first by her apparel, is crowned with the olive branch, \softline
traditionally symbolic of peace but also associated with wisdom, since the olive was sacred to the \softline
goddess of wisdom, Minerva.  The three colors that she wears associate her with faith (white), \softline
hope (green), and charity (red), the three theological virtues we have already seen in the \softline
procession (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXIX.121-126).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 34-36.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Beatrice died in June of 1290; it is now either the end of March or early April of \softline
1300 (see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.1) and thus about two months fewer than ten years since she died.  If \softline
the action of the poem indeed did begin, in Dante's mind, on Friday 25 March 1300 (see the note \softline
to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg.}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II.94-105), this day is Wednesday 30 March 1300 or 3/30/1300, literally a perfect day, a \softline
ten composed of three threes (Beatrice's number in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 VN}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIX.3 is nine, or three squared).  For a \softline
recent study of the numerological aspects of Beatrice see Carlo Vecce ("Beatrice e il numero \softline
amico," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Beatrice nell'opera di Dante e nella memoria europea 1290-1990}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. Maria Picchio \softline
Simonelli [Florence: Cadmo, 1994], pp. 101-35).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Virgil had been overcome by }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 stupore}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (amazement) a short while ago (see the note to \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXIX.55-57); now it is Dante's turn.  Not even the man who wrote of Beatrice can \softline
encompass the fact of her miraculous nature now that he finally experiences it directly and \softline
completely.  It will take him another }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  adequately to understand what she means.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 39.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The line is clearly reminiscent (if the reminiscence was apparently only first noted by \softline
Torraca in 1905 [comm. to vv. 34-39]) of the opening of Dante's lyric (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Rime}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XCI), 'Io sento s{\f3 \'58} \softline
d'Amor la gran possanza' (So much do I feel Love's mighty power).   Just as was the case with \softline
Matelda (see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXVIII.43-48), Dante's concupiscent memories and thoughts are \softline
at odds with the nature of Beatrice.  Yes, she looks exactly like the woman with whom he fell in \softline
love in Florence; but now it is clear (as it should have been then) that she loves him only in Christ.  \softline
This distinction will be insisted on at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXXII.7-9.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The difference in the loves represented by the earlier poem (composed in the middle years \softline
of the 1290s?) and by this one is emblematized by the capital letter of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Amor}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (Love, as in 'the god \softline
of Love,' Cupid) in the first, and its absence here.  It is, of course, impossible to know whether \softline
either or both of these words for }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 amor}{\plain \fs24 \f1  was in fact capitalized by Dante, especially since questions \softline
of punctuation and of capitalization in medieval manuscripts are simpy not resolvable (except, \softline
perhaps, when we have an autograph to guide us).  All one can say is that modern editors have \softline
done well in this instance, that it would make sense for Dante to have done as they have.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 40-42.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   For Dante's earlier references to his first being smitten by Beatrice while he was \softline
still in his childhood, in fact in his ninth year (i.e., while he was still eight), see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Vita nuova}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II.2 \softline
