}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 115-117.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   It seems obvious to most readers today that the phrase }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 vita nova}{\plain \fs24 \f1  refers, if in its \softline
Latin form, to Dante's first prosimetrum, the thirty-one poems collected with prose commentary \softline
known as }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 The New Life}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  And it seemed so to at least one very early commentator, the Ottimo (in \softline
1333, in his general note to the canto).  However, here is the commentary of Benvenuto da Imola \softline
to this passage (comm. to vv. 109-117): 'This man, i.e., Dante, was such in his new life, i.e., in his \softline
boyhood; others, however, refer to his treatise }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 De vita nova}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , which he composed in his youth.  \softline
But it is surely ridiculous to do so, seeing that the author was ashamed of it in his maturity.'  \softline
Benvenuto's enthusiastic pre-humanist reading of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Comedy}{\plain \fs24 \f1  will only accept an allegorical, \softline
theologized Beatrice who bears no resemblance to the mortal girl of the early work.  Thus does he \softline
fail to grasp the central pretext of the entire poem, and surely of this extended scene in the garden \softline
of Eden.  What seems most notable, perhaps, is the power of Benvenuto's opinion.  None of the \softline
other early commentators who follow him mentions the book as being referred to here.  It is only \softline
with Venturi (1732, comm. to verse 115) that we hear that it }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 may}{\plain \fs24 \f1  also be referred to; this over-cautious estimate will be found in several others, such as Portirelli (comm. to vv. 109-117), \softline
Mestica (comm. to verse 115), and Del Lungo (comm. to vv. 115-116).  It was, however, only \softline
Scartazzini -- as is so often the case -- who really tried to examine the issue frontally.  His solution \softline
(comm. to verse 115) was to argue that the literal sense of 'new life' was 'youth,' but that the \softline
phrase referred to the regeneration of Dante's virtue by agency of Beatrice.  One may feel it \softline
necessary to quibble with this estimate, since Dante first felt the power of Beatrice's goodness \softline
when he was just days from turning nine years old, and thus the traditional reading 'boyhood' \softline
(more disturbing to such as Scartazzini than 'youth') is correct.  Scartazzini, however, is \softline
uncompromising and probably convincing in sensing that the reference is to the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 libello}{\plain \fs24 \f1  as well.  \softline
How could it be otherwise?  One can see in this dispute, which continues in muffled form even \softline
today, an outline of the way commentators influence the readings of other commentators, and \softline
thus eventually teachers, and finally students.  Benvenuto's opinions are respected (and surely they \softline
should be, as he is clearly one of the most acute students of the poem), but sometimes slavishly.  \softline
Similarly, Scartazzini's insistent judgments, frequently overstated and often too assured, are \softline
avoided by later commentators, for perhaps a series of reasons.  Scartazzini was not only a 
German Swiss and a Protestant, but a Protestant clergyman.  And perhaps most annoying of all to \softline
an Italian reader, he loved to belittle his adversaries and thought little or nothing of most of his \softline
Italian colleagues.  One result of this, as a certain amount of consultation of the Dartmouth Dante \softline
Project will affirm, is that Scartazzini's tendentious and flawed but nonetheless great commentary \softline
(1900), reflecting the entries that were composed for his one-man }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Enciclopedia dantesca}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
(published in Milano in 1896 and 1899, and then reissued in 1905, edited by Fiammazzo), is both \softline
pillaged and avoided in silence by many of those who came after him.  For all his acerbity -- even \softline
nastiness -- his work deserves much more attention than it generally receives.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab One finds, even among recent commentators, a certain desire to avoid committing oneself \softline
to what seems completely obvious: the phrase }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 vita nova}{\plain \fs24 \f1  cannot help but call to mind, in this \softline
context, the work that records Beatrice's lasting impact on Dante, first in his 'new life' (when they \softline
were both children, a time to which Dante refers in verse 42: 'before I had outgrown my \softline
childhood') and then later on, as recorded in the book called 'The New Life.'\par
