}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 134.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The sort of dream Beatrice prayed God to send Dante is probably well represented \softline
by the dream of the Siren in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XIX.7-32.  That accounts for the first part of Beatrice's \softline
formulation, i.e., Dante was given negative dreams about his disastrous love for the wrong lady.  \softline
What about the second?  What God-sent 'inspirations' was she granted in order to call him back to \softline
loving her even after her death?  Scartazzini (comm. to vv. 133-134) offers a simple and \softline
compelling hypothesis (apparently silently acceded to by any number of later commentators, who \softline
make the same point without even a mention of his name).  In }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Vita nuova}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXXIX.1 Dante \softline
receives the image of the girlish Beatrice in his phantasy, the image-receiving part of his mind \softline
(one may compare the ecstatic visions vouchsafed him for the exemplary figures on the terrace of \softline
Wrath [and see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XV.85-114]).  As he recounts (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 VN}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXXIX.2-6), this vision of \softline
Beatrice had the necessary effect, and he resolved to love her yet again, turning away his affection \softline
from the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 donna gentile}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  And then, Scartazzini continues, he was allowed the final vision of \softline
Beatrice seated in the Empyrean (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 VN}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XLII.1).  Thus, as seems clear, while Dante slept, God sent \softline
him dreams of what was unworthy in his love for the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 donna gentile}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ; while he was awake, positive \softline
images of Beatrice.  If this program is correctly perceived, it matches precisely the mode \softline
employed to teach penitents on the mountain, positive and negative examples teaching what to \softline
follow and what to flee.  Unfortunately, even after such encouragement, Dante would fall again.  \softline
See the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXXIII.85-90.\par
