}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 139-141.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Poor Virgil!  He has done the Christians sixty-four cantos' worth of service, \softline
guiding their great poet to his redemption and vision, and now the very lady who sought his help \softline
does not even mention his name; he is but 'colui' (the one who).  Where is Virgil now?  On his 
way back to Limbo, we must assume.  And thus, we may also assume, to another sad welcome \softline
from his fellow poets once he is again (less than a week after he had already returned once [see \softline
the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IV.80-81]) among them in his }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 etterno essilio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (eternal exile -- }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXI.18).  We \softline
shall only hear his name twice more (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par. }{\plain \fs24 \f1 XVII.19 and XXVI.118) and never again from \softline
Beatrice, who only uses it once, in her first words, coupling it with Dante's (verse 55), and then to \softline
shame Dante for his affection for Virgil when there are more important feelings to be had.\par
